\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator stated that the programme in terms of all the criteria to be assessed for a public institution meet the minimum requirements for accreditation and recommended that the programme should be accredited with conditions related to criteria that public institutions are not required to provide information on.\line \line The programme is in line with the mission of the Institution. The proposed programme is a product of renewed thinking about the postgraduate CA programme offering of the School of Accountancy and Faculty of Economic and Management Sciences. These outcomes are achieved by structuring four compulsory modules\'2C namely\'2C Auditing\'2C Governance and Information Systems\'2C Financial Accounting\'2C Management Accounting and Finance and Taxation. The above-mentioned modules and the credit weighting seem adequate and cover the functional\'2C practical and theoretical aspects that would be expected from CA. This structure and the modules are similar to that of other SAICA approved programmes.\line \line The articulation after the successful completion of the PGDip in Accounting could be a Master\'27s Degree or a Professional Master\'27s Degree in Accounting or a cognate discipline\'2C such as Management Accounting\'2C Auditing and Taxation \'28NQF level 9\'29. \line \line Students applying should have attained a degree in BAcc or BAccLLB from the University of Stellenbosch or an equivalent qualification from another university with a weighted average performance mark of at least 60\'25. Although the Institution has not mentioned RPL for student admission\'2C the Institution has attached its RPL Policy. \line \line As this is a public institution\'2C Criteria 3\'2C 4\'2C 7 and 8 are deemed to be the responsibility of the Institution.\line \line Face-to-face contact sessions play a major role as part of the mode of offering the programme. Large tutorials\'2C case study feedback sessions and extensive self-study will also be utilized. The School of Accountancy also operates a \'28Individual Learning and Assistance Programme \'28ILP\'29 which takes place every weekday directly after the mainstream lectures\'2C to assist students struggling with certain concepts. Blended learning through the online platform uses various modes of content delivery. Class notes are available online\'2C email communication with fellow students are encouraged\'2C the use on computers during the course is imperative and occasional engagement with podcasts will be needed in preparation for lectures. Additional contact time with lecturers will be available 8 hours per week. No additional significant material development is required\'2C as these modules already exist on the B Acc Hons programme. In addition\'2C to the aforementioned\'2C summer and winter schools are presented to SAICA Thuthuka bursary students\'2C aimed at revision specific challenging topics before the commencement of formal lectures.\line \line The three scheduled class tests will be written on Saturdays\'2C followed by March and September term tests\'2C a June \'28mid-year\'29 semester test and a November examination and supplementary examination. All assessments are open book assessments and will include reading time\'2C as this is consistent with SAIC\'27s assessment of Initial Test of Competency \'28ITC\'29 and it prepares students for the ITC. The programme has appropriate policies for internal assessments. \line \line Students will receive their assessment attempts back with suggested solution and mark plan and where applicable the necessary notes and feedback\'2C affording the student the opportunity to discuss the scripts with lecturers and to learn from their mistakes. \line \line The Directorate recommends that the programme be accredited.\cell \pard 

